The paper discusses a neural architecture and unsupervised algorithm for learning invariant representations from temporal sequences of images. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of an encoder and decoder, which are commonly used in neural networks for tasks such as image reconstruction and generation, indicating that the paper may also belong to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. The paper discusses the use of sparsity constraints, which are commonly used in machine learning for tasks such as feature selection and regularization, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions the emergence of orientation-selective receptive fields, which are a characteristic feature of the mammalian visual cortex, indicating that the paper may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the organization of feature units into pinwheel patterns, which is a spatial pattern commonly observed in natural images, suggesting that the paper may also belong to the signal processing (cs.SD) sub-category.
